review_blob: Pours deep brown with an off-white head. Aroma consists of oats and honey, with hints of coffee. Very unique and delicious beer, although it could be a lot thicker in my opinion.

Pours a deep brown with a small off-white head. Aroma consists of caramel and nuts. The 10% abv is hidden incredibly well. Taste consists of rich caramel, vanilla, scotch, and roasted nuts. Absolutely delicious and very drinkable ale. A+  Looking forward to trying more from Alesmith.

On draught at Eastside Club Tavern in Olympia. Pours a deep black with off-white head. Aroma is fruits and chocolate. Sour hits you instantly and then fades nicely into the coffee/chocolate of the stout. Great beer. Probably the only thing I have really liked from New Belgium.
beer_name: New Belgium Lips of Faith - Clutch

review_blob: On draught  - pours a nice deep brown with an off-white head. Aroma consists of caramel and pine. Taste is very rich with more caramel and a hint of nut/pine. Could definitely be thicker and the abv is a bit low for my taste, but a very well crafted porter nonetheless.

Poured from a bottle purchased at Good Beer in New York. Comes out a beautiful dark brown. Has a nice thick almost syrup-like density. Aroma consists of caramel, vanilla, and alcohol. Very dense and complex beer, lots to love. Recommended.

From the bottle - purchased at Good Beer in New York. Nice sharp bite on the tongue - lots of citrus namely grapefruit. Goes down very smooth. Could be a bit heavier but thats just my preference. Over all a good ale.
beer_name: Ballast Point / Kelsey McNair / Stone San Diego County Session Ale

review_blob: Pours a nice golden-orange with a thin white head. Aroma is fruity and warm. Has a nice bite of alcohol, goes down relatively smooth. Overall an excellent ale. Definitely has that "brewed by monks" feel.

Pours a nice deep black with a thin brown head that disappeared very quickly. Aroma consists of roasted nuts and espresso. The chocolate has a very nice presence - very bitter and dark. The bitterness is almost too much though, especially in combination with the hops and bite of the alcohol. Though still a well-crafted and tasty beer, not my favorite stout.

Pours a beautiful gold with a white head. Very refreshing beer, hints of fruit and spices - very full bodied. Again has that north coast signature - although it may not be my favorite of their beers it is a very accurate representation of the belgian style ale.

Pours a deep brown-red with a nice tan head. Aroma is sweet and fruity with hints of alcohol. Very tasty -hints of coffee, caramel, and citrus. The alcohol could be hidden a bit better.. Goes very well with dark bread. Overall a great ale, North Coast definitely have a signature they leave in all their beers - this one is no exception.

Pours golden ("piss" color if  you will) with a white head. Im not really one for lagers but this was definitely decent. Very "refreshing" and did a good job of washing down my thai food. Has a bit of a fruity aftertaste. Although in retrospect I should have just stuck with water and saved myself 2$. Better than most popular american lagers for sure.

Pours brown with a very minimal head. Aroma consists of nuts and coffee. Taste is smokey with hints of coffee as well. Resonates nicely on the tongue. Overall a decent yet tasty porter, but not something to go out of my way for. Especially with the $10 per bottle price. Yikes. Still it has intrigued me enough to try more beers by Great Divide.
Pours black with a tan head. Nice hints of coffee and raisins, overall a decent stout - definitely on the more "drinkable" side. Could be a bit thicker.
Pours pitch black with a beautiful brown head. Aroma of grapes and citrus. Comes in smooth and leaves with a hard kick of alcohol. Incredible beer. Stone once again can do no wrong.
beer_name: Stone 15th Anniversary Escondidian Imperial Black IPA

review_blob: Pours golden with a white head, a bit of fruit in the aroma. Has a delicious bitter finish, very refreshing. Overall a great pale ale, but not mind blowing. Looking forward to trying more of Lagunitas brews.
Pours amber with a white head, decent flavor but overall pretty watered down. The aroma is probably its strongest feature. A drinkable but relatively uninteresting ale.

Would be great on a really hot day because it has the consistency of water. Decent flavor, although nothing really stands out. Light even for a hefeweizen, Although it wasnt horrible by any means, its not my kind of beer.
Pours dark with a white head, aroma consists of fine cheeses and fruit (would probably go well with both). The 9% doesnt come through at all in the taste, very full bodied and rich. Excellent ale.

Pours golden with a white head. The grapes come through in a big way, almost too much for me maybe. Almost tastes more like wine or a lager than an ale. Still excellent, as to be expected from stone. I would be interested to try the other years.
Head disappeared almost immediately-pours a nice amber color. Well balanced flavor as well as good density and abv. Overall a great IPA. Definitely something to look for.
Pours amber with a thin white head, lots of honey and biscuit overtones. Flavor is thinner than the aroma. Overall a "decent" beer, but not something I would come back to.

Pours black with a beautiful dark brown head. Delicious all around - the typical coffee and chocolate you find in a good stout but this one is really done well. Nice and thick, everything I like in a stout. Overall an incredible stout, will definitely look for it again as well as try more from Nogne O.

To be honest I was expecting something better from Guinness. Definitely an overhyped beer, although not bad by any means. Pours black with a tan head, has a roasty aroma. Relatively bitter without too much complexity. Also too thin for my taste. A decent stout, but nothing to go out of my way for.
Overall a pretty decent stout, although it doesnt blow me away. The aftertaste is very sweet which is pretty unusual and makes it fairly unique. Has a relatively light consistency, could be thicker.

I was pretty blown away by this beer, definitely high up there for a porter. Very strong initially with lots of alcohol and coffee. Pours a beautiful dark brown. Simply Delicious - PLUS it pays tribute to Hunter S. Thompson. Cant go wrong.
Aroma was initially very much alcohol, also very chocolately of course. Definitely could be a bit thicker. Probably the thinnest stout Ive had, although it is still very good. Resonates very nicely.
Pours a nice caramel brown. The hazelnut flavor is very much prevalent. Aftertaste has a bit of coffee/caramel flavor. Overall a pretty good ale, although it could be a bit thicker.
Definitely one of my favorite Pale Ales. Goes down smooth with a great finish.

I cant get enough of this stout. Definitely the darkest beer Ive ever seen - I get a tingle down my spine every time I pour it. Like it says on the bottle, "pours like motor oil".  the anise and coffee give it an extra edge that will leave you with a grin on your face. Stone brewery proves again that they can do no wrong.

This beer is everything a stout should be. Rich, dark, and very - did I mention rich? Full bodied flavor that resonates deeply in your mouth after you have finished the glass. Definitely will not disappoint. Highly recommended.
beer_name: North Coast Old Rasputin Russian Imperial Stout

review_blob: Very smooth for such a rich and complex beer. Rests easily on the palate. Has a slightly sweet and woodsy aftertaste that makes you anxious for more. Makes me want to try more of Brewdogs brews. Highly recommended.
